    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>After the Breakup</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kathleen Carlsson letter on American Law Institute proposal that states update their family law (Nov 30 article), objecting to proposal to expand right to alimony and asset reallocation for former spouses</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Group Urges States to Update Their Family Law'' (front page, Nov. 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Group Urges States to Update Their Family Law'' (front page, Nov. 30):</p>
        <p>As a lawyer, I object to the proposal by the American Law Institute to expand the right to alimony and asset reallocation for former spouses. The availability of these remedies should be narrowed rather than expanded. The law should not encourage women to be less self-reliant.</p>
        <p>As to unmarried couples, why bring them into a mandatory legal system instead of simply leaving them with the right to individually enter into contracts or make gifts? A law that would make unmarried couples liable for each other's support would cause havoc with long-term care planning for the elderly. At present, as long as they are not married, neither party is responsible for the other's cost of care. If they became liable, a lifetime of asset accumulation would be at stake.</p>
        <p>KATHLEEN CARLSSON  Sayville, N.Y., Nov. 30, 2002</p>
      </block>
